						               													<description>Literally meaning &amp;lsquo;Soldier Shogi&amp;rsquo;, Gunjin Shogi is not really related to Shogi other than by having a military theme and pentagonal pieces. The game is more similar to Army Chess (Lu Zhan Jun Qi) or Stratego, featuring hidden pieces and a hierarchical system of combat, where higher ranked pieces defeat lower ones: the objective is to capture the opponent&amp;rsquo;s flag. Like Army Chess, Gunjin Shogi requires a third person to act as umpire and resolve combat. Unlike Army Chess (and more like Hai Lu Kong Jun Qi), Gunjin Shogi includes planes and tanks.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each player has 23 pieces, consisting of a flag, 12 officers, 2 planes, 2 tanks, a cavalry unit, two engineers, a spy and two land mines. There is a hierarchy of ranks, with some exceptions &amp;ndash; planes naturally cannot be destroyed by land mines and engineers deactivate land mines, for instance.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game dates to at least before the second world war (I base this on an incomplete pre-war set I was shown in an antique shop in Japan).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
